I have the full picture. Here is the complete diagnosis, fix, and documentation.

---

## Diagnosis

The layout tree in `src/app/(frontend)/(site)/layout.tsx` is:

```
<div class="siteWrapper">          ← flex column, min-height: 100vh
  <nav class="nav">                ← position: sticky  ← THIS IS THE CHROME
  <div class="contentArea">        ← overflow-x: auto  ← scroll container
    <div class="contentAreaInner"> ← min-width: 672px  ← floor
  <SiteFooter />
```

The intent from FB-149 was correct: `overflow-x: auto` on `.contentArea` should contain the 672px floor so the document width never expands, leaving the sticky nav free to track the actual viewport. But there's a critical CSS containment failure: **`overflow-x: auto` only creates a scroll container when its content actually overflows it — and that only happens if the scroll container itself has a constrained width.** A flex child with `flex: 1` and `min-width: 0` has a constrained block size, but its *inline* size is determined by the flex parent (`.siteWrapper`), which has no `overflow-x` constraint and no explicit width. When `.contentAreaInner` is set to `min-width: 672px` and the viewport is, say, 200px wide, `.contentArea`'s computed width becomes 672px (driven upward by its child), `.siteWrapper` expands to 672px, and the browser makes the **document** 672px wide. At that point the sticky nav tracks the 672px document — it is not clipped by the viewport, but the viewport cannot scroll horizontally because `html` and `body` have no `overflow-x: auto`. The right edge of the nav is simply beyond the viewport edge with no scroll handle.

**Root cause:** AP-067 — *Min-Width Floor on a Root Wrapper That Contains Functional Chrome.* The existing AP-067 documents exactly this class of bug from FB-149, but the implementation did not fully solve it: `overflow-x: auto` on a flex child is not sufficient to prevent document-width inflation. The scroll container must also be given `width: 100%` (pinning it to the viewport, not to its children) so it cannot be stretched wider than the viewport by its floored child.

---

## Fix

Three changes across two files, plus documentation updates.

### 1. `src/app/(frontend)/(site)/layout.module.scss`

The `overflow-x: auto` block is in the right place (`.contentArea`, not `.siteWrapper`), but the scroll container is missing `width: 100%` to pin itself to the viewport. Without it, a flex child's `min-width` inflates the flex parent, which inflates `.siteWrapper`, which inflates the document.

```scss
// BEFORE
@media (pointer: fine) and (max-width: #{$elan-bp-sm - 1px}) {
  .contentArea {
    overflow-x: auto;
  }

  .contentAreaInner {
    min-width: $elan-bp-sm;
  }
}
```

```scss
// AFTER
@media (pointer: fine) and (max-width: #{$elan-bp-sm - 1px}) {
  .contentArea {
    // Pin the scroll container to the viewport width so its floored child
    // cannot push the document (and the sticky nav) wider than 100vw.
    // Without this, overflow-x: auto is a no-op — the flex parent inflates
    // to match the child's min-width, making the document itself wider than
    // the viewport, with no horizontal scrollbar (AP-067 second vector).
    width: 100%;
    overflow-x: auto;
  }

  .contentAreaInner {
    min-width: $elan-bp-sm;
  }
}
```

### 2. `src/components/ui/Navigation/Navigation.module.scss`

The nav is `position: sticky` — it tracks the document scroll container, not the viewport. It needs `width: 100%` (already the default for block-level elements, but must be made explicit here) **and** `max-width: 100vw` to hard-cap it to the viewport. This is a belt-and-suspenders guard: if any future refactor makes the document wider than the viewport again, the nav will still never exceed the viewport.

```scss
// BEFORE
.nav {
  position: sticky;
  top: 0;
  z-index: var(--portfolio-z-sticky);
  background-color: var(--portfolio-surface-terra-subtle);
  box-shadow: 0 4px 12px -4px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.05);
  ...
```

```scss
// AFTER
.nav {
  position: sticky;
  top: 0;
  // Hard-cap the nav to the viewport width. A sticky element tracks the
  // document's block formatting context, not the viewport — if the document
  // is ever wider than the viewport (e.g. an overflow-x: auto scroll container
  // fails to contain a floored child), the nav would be clipped or unreachable.
  // max-width: 100vw ensures functional chrome is always fully reachable at
  // any viewport width regardless of content overflow. See AP-067.
  width: 100%;
  max-width: 100vw;
  z-index: var(--portfolio-z-sticky);
  background-color: var(--portfolio-surface-terra-subtle);
  box-shadow: 0 4px 12px -4px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.05);
  ...
```

### 3. Documentation: amend `AP-067` in `docs/design-anti-patterns.md`

AP-067 documents the first vector (putting `min-width` on `.siteWrapper` directly). Extend it with a **second vector** covering the containment failure discovered here, and add a reference to FB-225.

Find the existing AP-067 block (after AP-066) and replace it with:

```markdown
<a id="ap-067"></a>
## AP-067: Min-Width Floor on a Root Wrapper That Contains Functional Chrome

**Status: ACTIVE** *(amended FB-225 — second vector added)*

### Vector 1 (original — FB-149): `min-width` on `.siteWrapper` directly

**Trigger:** Putting `min-width: 672px` (or any fixed floor) on the `.siteWrapper` flex root that also contains the Navigation and SiteFooter.

**Why it's wrong:** `.siteWrapper` is the document's root flex container. A `min-width` here expands the *document* width. When the document is wider than the viewport, `position: sticky` nav tracks the document — it renders off-screen to the right and is unreachable because the page root has no horizontal scroll handle.

**Correct alternative:** The floor goes on `.contentAreaInner` only. `.contentArea` (the flex sibling of the nav, not the parent wrapper) gets `overflow-x: auto` to contain the overflow. Functional chrome (nav, footer) stays at viewport width.

---

### Vector 2 (FB-225): `overflow-x: auto` scroll container not pinned to viewport width

**Trigger:** Placing `overflow-x: auto` on a flex child (`.contentArea`) without also setting `width: 100%` on that child. The child has `min-width: 0` but no explicit width.

**Why it's wrong:** A flex child's computed inline size is the *maximum* of its `min-width` constraint and its flex-layout-assigned size. If the child contains a `min-width: 672px` grandchild, the flex child is sized *up* to 672px by its content — it is no longer constrained to the viewport. The `overflow-x: auto` fires only when the scroll container is narrower than its content. Without `width: 100%`, the container inflates to match the content, no overflow is detected, no scrollbar appears, and the document becomes 672px wide. The sticky nav inherits document width, not viewport width — it is unreachable on viewports narrower than 672px.

**Correct alternative:**
```scss
// The scroll container must be pinned to the viewport so its floored child
// actually overflows it rather than inflating it.
.contentArea {
  width: 100%;          // ← pin to flex-parent / viewport width
  overflow-x: auto;     // ← now fires correctly when child > 100%
}
.contentAreaInner {
  min-width: $elan-bp-sm;  // ← floor on content only
}
```

Additionally, add `max-width: 100vw` to the nav itself as a hard backstop:
```scss
.nav {
  position: sticky;
  width: 100%;
  max-width: 100vw;   // ← nav never exceeds viewport regardless of document width
}
```

**Frustration caused:** 1 round. Functional chrome (nav) clipped and unreachable at viewports < 320px; no horizontal scroll appeared despite `overflow-x: auto` being present.

**Related:** Vector 1 above; FB-147; FB-149; `docs/design/responsive.md` §6.10.
```

### 4. Documentation: append to `docs/design-feedback-log.md`

Prepend FB-225 to the top of the log (newest first):

```markdown
#### FB-225: "The entire page stops scrolling horizontally — nav clipped on the right"

**UX Intent:** Functional chrome (sticky nav) must be reachable at any viewport width. A nav item that is visually present but cannot be scrolled to is worse than invisible — it signals a broken page.
**Root Cause:** `overflow-x: auto` on `.contentArea` (a flex child) was missing `width: 100%`. Without pinning the scroll container to the viewport, the flex child's size was driven upward to match its `min-width: 672px` grandchild, inflating the document width. The sticky nav tracked document width, not viewport width, so it extended off-screen with no horizontal scroll handle on the page root.
**Resolution:** Added `width: 100%` to `.contentArea` inside the `pointer: fine` media query in `layout.module.scss`. Added `max-width: 100vw` to `.nav` in `Navigation.module.scss` as a hard backstop. AP-067 amended with second vector (Vector 2).
**Pattern extracted → `design-anti-patterns.md` AP-067 Vector 2: overflow-x scroll container not pinned to viewport width.**
```

### 5. Update the `docs/design-anti-patterns.md` header note

The `Last updated` line at the top of the file becomes:

```
**Last updated:** 2026-XX-XX (AP-067 amended: second vector added — `overflow-x: auto` scroll container not pinned to viewport width causes document inflation and sticky nav clipping at sub-320px viewports. FB-225.) Prior: ...
```

---

## Principle

**AP-067, Vector 2 — The Containment Contract:**

> An `overflow-x: auto` scroll container only works when it is **narrower than its content**. A flex child whose size is governed by its children's `min-width` — not by the flex parent — will inflate to match that `min-width`, satisfying the containment contract from the wrong direction. The fix is always `width: 100%` on the scroll container (pinning it to its parent/viewport) *before* relying on `overflow-x: auto` to catch the child's floor.
>
> As a belt-and-suspenders rule: **functional chrome (nav, footer) should always carry `max-width: 100vw`**, because a sticky element tracks the document's block formatting context — if the document is ever wider than the viewport for any reason, chrome without this cap becomes unreachable.
